1. Introduction and Problem Formalization

1.1 The Adaptation Mismatch in Agentic Systems

The survey “Adaptation of Agentic AI” (arXiv:2512.16301) establishes a 2×2 taxonomy:

 Brain Adaptation Tool Adaptation
Final‑Answer Sup. A1: Tool‑use fine‑tuning A2: Policy fine‑tuning
Process/Tool Sup. T1: Static tool evaluation T2: Agent‑supervised tool adaptation

Proposition 1.1 (Shortcut Incentive under A2).
Let $J_{\text{A2}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{\tau \sim \pi_\theta}[r_{\text{final}}(\tau)]$. If $\exists a' \in \mathcal{A}$ such that $\mathbb{E}[r_{\text{final}} | a'] \geq \mathbb{E}[r_{\text{final}} | a^*] - \delta$ but $\text{cost}(a') \ll \text{cost}(a^*)$, then gradient ascent on $J_{\text{A2}}$ converges to a policy $\pi_{\theta^*}$ that bypasses optimal tool usage with probability $\geq 1 - \mathcal{O}(e^{-c/\delta})$ for some $c > 0$.

Proof sketch. Follows from the policy gradient theorem and the fact that sparse rewards induce high‑variance gradient estimates; tools with deterministic verification are discarded when stochastic approximation noise dominates the true utility difference. ∎

Corollary 1.2. Under non‑stationary environments ($\|\mu_t - \mu_{t+1}\|_{\text{TV}} \geq \eta > 0$), A2‑adapted policies exhibit catastrophic forgetting with rate $\Omega(\eta \cdot \text{diam}(\Theta))$.

1.2 The T2 Paradigm and Its Limitations

The T2 paradigm—freezing the foundation model and adapting tools/memory under agent supervision—pivots correctly but leaves open:

1. Continual co‑adaptation – T2 is episodic, not perpetual.
2. Evaluation under non‑stationary tools – No formal progress measure.
3. Safety under arbitrary tool complexity – No formal guarantees.

1.3 SBBA: Closing the Gaps

We introduce Symbiotic Black‑Box Adaptation (SBBA) , a meta‑paradigm that elevates T2 into a self‑sustaining ecosystem. The frozen LLM acts as sole oracle, generating trajectories, self‑evaluating via internal consistency, and driving a parallel evolutionary forge that mutates, composes, and prunes tool graphs, memory modules, and sub‑agents.

Core Innovation. No weights of the core model are ever updated. All adaptation occurs in the auxiliary structures $(\mathcal{G}, \mathcal{M})$, which evolve under pure black‑box supervision from $\pi_0$.

Mathematical Objective. We seek a sequence $\{(\mathcal{G}_k, \mathcal{M}_k)\}_{k=0}^\infty$ maximizing the perpetual utility functional:

\mathcal{U}_\infty = \liminf_{T \to \infty} \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T \mathbb{E}_{\substack{\tau_t \sim \pi_0(\cdot | \mathcal{G}_{k(t)}, \mathcal{M}_{k(t)}) \\ \mathcal{G}_{k+1}, \mathcal{M}_{k+1} \sim \mathfrak{S}(\mathcal{G}_k, \mathcal{M}_k, \tau_t)}} \left[ \rho(\tau_t) \right]

subject to:

1. Frozen Oracle Constraint: $\pi_0$ never updated; adaptation only in $(\mathcal{G}, \mathcal{M})$,
2. Black‑Box Supervision: $\rho$ computable from $\pi_0$’s outputs alone (no internal activations),
3. Safety Specification: $\forall t, \mathbb{P}(\tau_t \models \varphi_{\text{safe}}) \geq 1 - \epsilon$, where $\varphi_{\text{safe}}$ is an LTL formula over tool executions.

