5. Theoretical Guarantees: Complete Proofs

5.1 Proof of Lemma 3.3.2 (Tournament Selection Improvement)

Proof.

Step 1: Order statistics for tournament selection.
Let $X_1, \dots, X_s$ be i.i.d. samples from the population fitness distribution with CDF $F$. The expected maximum is
\mathbb{E}[\max_i X_i] = \int_0^\infty (1 - F(x)^s) \,dx = \mu + \int_0^\infty (1 - F(x)^s - \mathbb{I}[x < \mu]) \,dx.


For a finite population of size $n$ with empirical CDF $\hat{F}_n$, the bias correction gives
\mathbb{E}[\max_i X_i \mid \text{pop}] = \mu_n + \frac{\sigma_n^2}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right) + o(1/n),


where $\mu_n, \sigma_n^2$ are sample mean and variance.

Step 2: Mutation penalty bound.
Let $G_{\text{parent}}$ be a selected parent and $G_{\text{offspring}} \sim K_{\text{mut}}(\cdot \mid G_{\text{parent}})$. By Lipschitz fitness (A1),
|f(G_{\text{offspring}}) - f(G_{\text{parent}})| \leq L \cdot d_{\text{edit}}(G_{\text{offspring}}, G_{\text{parent}}).


Taking expectation and using $\mathbb{E}[d_{\text{edit}}] \leq \epsilon_{\text{mut}}$ gives
\mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{offspring}}) \mid G_{\text{parent}}] \geq f(G_{\text{parent}}) - L \epsilon_{\text{mut}}.

Step 3: Combine via law of total expectation.
Conditioning on the selection event,
\begin{aligned}
f_{k+1} &= \mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{offspring}})] \\
&= \mathbb{E}\bigl[\mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{offspring}}) \mid G_{\text{parent}}]\bigr] \\
&\geq \mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{parent}})] - L \epsilon_{\text{mut}} \\
&\geq f_k + \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\rho)}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right) - L \epsilon_{\text{mut}}.
\end{aligned}


∎

5.2 Proof of Theorem 4.1 (Additive Drift)

Theorem 4.1 (Additive Drift). Under the same conditions as Lemma 3.3.2, the expected one‑generation improvement satisfies
\mathbb{E}[f_{k+1} - f_k \mid \mathcal{G}_k] \geq \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\rho)}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right) - L \cdot \mathbb{E}[d_{\text{edit}}].


If additionally $\mathbb{E}[d_{\text{edit}}] < \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\rho)}{L s}(1-1/n)$, then the drift is positive.

Proof. Immediate from Lemma 3.3.2 by taking conditional expectation and noting that $\epsilon_{\text{mut}} = \mathbb{E}[d_{\text{edit}}]$. ∎

5.3 Proof of Theorem 3.4.2 (Level‑Based Convergence)

Proof. This is a direct application of the level‑based convergence theorem for non‑elitist evolutionary algorithms (Lehre & Qin, 2022, Theorem 1). The drift condition from Lemma 3.3.2 ensures that from any level $L_i$, the probability of producing an individual in a higher level within $t_i$ generations is at least $\gamma_i$. The expected time to leave $L_i$ is at most $t_i/\gamma_i$. Summing over levels gives the bound. The polynomial dependence on $1/\epsilon$ follows from the minimum level gap $\Delta_{\min}$ and the total fitness range. ∎

5.4 Theorem 4.3: Finite‑Sample PAC Bound

Theorem 4.3 (Uniform Convergence of Fitness Estimates).
Let $\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}} \subseteq \mathcal{G}$ be the effective set of tool graphs reachable by SBBA (e.g., those with bounded description length). Let $f(G) = \mathbb{E}[\rho(\tau\mid G)]$ and $\hat{f}_T(G) = \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^T \rho(\tau_t\mid G)$ be the empirical average after $T$ independent trajectories (each generated by a fresh rollout of $\pi_0$ conditioned on $G$). Assume $|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}| < \infty$ (or a covering number bound). Then for any $\delta \in (0,1)$, with probability at least $1-\delta$,
\sup_{G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}} |\hat{f}_T(G) - f(G)| \leq \sqrt{\frac{\log(2|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}|/\delta)}{2T}}.


Consequently, the best empirical graph satisfies $f(\hat{G}_T) \geq \max_{G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}} f(G) - \sqrt{\frac{2\log(2|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}|/\delta)}{T}}$.

Proof. For each fixed $G$, the random variables $\rho(\tau_t\mid G)$ are i.i.d. bounded in $[0,1]$. By Hoeffding’s inequality,
\mathbb{P}(|\hat{f}_T(G) - f(G)| \geq \epsilon) \leq 2\exp(-2T\epsilon^2).


Take a union bound over all $G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}$ and set $\epsilon = \sqrt{\frac{\log(2|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}|/\delta)}{2T}}$. The second statement follows from the definition of supremum. ∎

Remark. When $|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}|$ is infinite, we can replace it with the covering number at scale $\epsilon$ and use a standard chaining argument. The logarithmic dependence on the covering number yields the same $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\log N/T})$ rate.

5.5 Safety Closure Under Evolutionary Operators

Definition 5.1 (Monitor‑Compatible Operator).
A mutation operator $K_{\text{mut}}$ is safe if for any $G$ satisfying $\mathbb{P}(\tau \models \varphi_{\text{safe}} \mid G) \geq 1-\epsilon$, the offspring $G'$ satisfies the same bound with probability at least $1-\nu$, where $\nu$ depends on the operator’s failure probability.

Theorem 5.2 (Safety Closure).
Suppose each atomic tool $v$ has failure probability $\mathbb{P}(v \text{ violates spec}) \leq \epsilon_v$. Let the monitor $\mathcal{A}_\varphi$ be synthesized as in Theorem 3.4. If the mutation and crossover operators are implemented as monitor‑guided (i.e., they reject any offspring that would cause the monitor to enter a rejecting state), then for any generation $k$,
\mathbb{P}(G_{k+1} \models \varphi_{\text{safe}} \mid G_k \models \varphi_{\text{safe}}) \geq 1 - \sum_{v \in \text{modified tools}} \epsilon_v.


In particular, if each modification touches at most $r$ tools, then the per‑generation safety violation probability is at most $r \cdot \max_v \epsilon_v$.

Proof. Monitor‑guided rejection ensures that only graphs that pass the monitor’s acceptance condition are retained. The only remaining risk is that the monitor itself may be imperfect due to atomic tool failures during execution. However, by Theorem 3.4, the monitor correctly detects violations if any atomic tool fails. The probability that any modified tool fails is at most the sum of individual failure probabilities (union bound). Thus the safety condition holds with probability at least $1 - \sum \epsilon_v$. ∎

