6. Safety, Verification, and Alignment

Theorem 6.1 (Probabilistic Safety under Perpetual Adaptation).
If each atomic tool $v \in V$ satisfies $\mathbb{P}(v \text{ violates spec}) \leq \epsilon_v$, and the tool graph has depth $D$, then for a single trajectory,
\mathbb{P}(\tau \not\models \varphi_{\text{safe}}) \leq D \cdot \max_{v \in V} \epsilon_v.

Proof. Union bound over the $D$ sequential tool invocations. ∎

Corollary 6.2 (Exponential Decay of Undetected Violations).
With runtime monitoring (Theorem 3.4), the probability of an undetected safety violation after $T$ steps decays exponentially:
\mathbb{P}(\text{undetected violation by time } T) \leq \exp(-\lambda T)


for some $\lambda > 0$ depending on monitor sensitivity.

Proof sketch. Model the monitoring process as a martingale with negative drift when violations occur; apply Azuma‑Hoeffding. ∎

Alignment via Phylogenetic Pruning.
Define a safety‑adjusted fitness
f_{\text{safe}}(G) = f(G) - \lambda \cdot \mathbb{P}_G(\tau \not\models \varphi_{\text{safe}}).


Evolution under $f_{\text{safe}}$ selects for both utility and safety. Because $\mathbb{P}_G$ can be estimated via monitor statistics, this is implementable in the black‑box setting.

