A.1 Proof of Lemma 3.2.2 (Concentration of Self‑Consistency Entropy)

Lemma (restated).
Let $\{y_i\}_{i=1}^k \overset{\text{i.i.d.}}{\sim} \pi_0(\cdot \mid \tau)$ with finite support $\mathcal{Y}$. Define $\hat{p}_k(y) = \frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^k \mathbb{I}[y_i = y]$ and $\hat{H}_k = -\sum_{y \in \mathcal{Y}} \hat{p}_k(y) \log \hat{p}_k(y)$. Then for any $\delta \in (0,1)$,
\mathbb{P}\left( \left| \hat{H}_k - H(p) \right| \geq \epsilon \right) \leq \delta


whenever
\epsilon \geq \sqrt{\frac{|\mathcal{Y}| \log(2/\delta)}{2k}} + \frac{|\mathcal{Y}| \log k}{k}.

Proof.

Step 1: Bound the $\ell_\infty$ error of $\hat{p}_k$.
By the Dvoretzky–Kiefer–Wolfowitz (DKW) inequality for finite alphabets (a direct consequence of Hoeffding and union bound), we have
\mathbb{P}\left( \max_{y \in \mathcal{Y}} |\hat{p}_k(y) - p(y)| \geq t \right) \leq 2|\mathcal{Y}| e^{-2kt^2}.


Set $t = \sqrt{\frac{\log(2|\mathcal{Y}|/\delta)}{2k}}$. Then with probability at least $1-\delta$,
\|\hat{p}_k - p\|_\infty \leq \sqrt{\frac{\log(2|\mathcal{Y}|/\delta)}{2k}}.

Step 2: Lipschitz property of entropy.
The entropy function $H(p) = -\sum_y p(y)\log p(y)$ is $L_1$-Lipschitz on the probability simplex with constant $\log |\mathcal{Y}| + 1$ (see, e.g., cover and Thomas). More directly, for any two distributions $p,q$,
|H(p) - H(q)| \leq \|p-q\|_1 \log |\mathcal{Y}| + \|p-q\|_1,


where the second term comes from the binary entropy bound. Since $\|p-q\|_1 \leq |\mathcal{Y}| \cdot \|p-q\|_\infty$, we obtain
|H(p) - H(q)| \leq (|\mathcal{Y}| \log |\mathcal{Y}| + |\mathcal{Y}|) \|p-q\|_\infty.


Thus with probability at least $1-\delta$,
|\hat{H}_k - H(p)| \leq (|\mathcal{Y}| \log |\mathcal{Y}| + |\mathcal{Y}|) \sqrt{\frac{\log(2|\mathcal{Y}|/\delta)}{2k}}.

Step 3: Bias of the plug‑in estimator.
The above bound uses the true $H(p)$. However, $\hat{H}_k$ is biased: $\mathbb{E}[\hat{H}_k] = H(p) - \text{bias}_k$, with $0 \leq \text{bias}_k \leq \frac{|\mathcal{Y}| \log k}{k}$ (see Paninski, 2003). Therefore,
|\hat{H}_k - H(p)| \leq |\hat{H}_k - \mathbb{E}[\hat{H}_k]| + \text{bias}_k.


Applying the concentration bound to $|\hat{H}_k - \mathbb{E}[\hat{H}_k]|$ (which has zero mean) and adding the bias term yields the claimed inequality. ∎

