A.3 Proof of Lemma 3.3.2 (Tournament Selection Improvement)

Lemma (restated).
Let $f_k = \mathbb{E}_{\tau \sim \pi_0(\cdot|\mathcal{G}_k,\mathcal{M}_k)}[\rho(\tau)]$ be the population‑mean fitness. Under tournament selection of size $s \geq 2$, Lipschitz fitness (A1), and mutation kernel with $\mathbb{E}[d_{\text{edit}}(G, G')] \leq \epsilon_{\text{mut}}$,
f_{k+1} \geq f_k + \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\rho)}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right) - L \epsilon_{\text{mut}}.

Proof.

Step 1: Expected fitness of the selected parent.
Let the population at generation $k$ consist of $n$ individuals with fitness values $F_1, \dots, F_n$ (random). Tournament selection picks $s$ individuals uniformly at random with replacement and selects the one with highest fitness. Denote $F_{\text{sel}}$ as the fitness of the selected parent. For i.i.d. samples from the empirical distribution, the expected value of the maximum of $s$ draws is
\mathbb{E}[F_{\text{sel}} \mid \text{pop}] = \mu_n + \frac{\sigma_n^2}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right) + o(1/n),


where $\mu_n = \frac{1}{n}\sum_i F_i$ and $\sigma_n^2 = \frac{1}{n}\sum_i (F_i - \mu_n)^2$. This is a standard result in order statistics for finite populations (see, e.g., Arnold, Balakrishnan, Nagaraja, A First Course in Order Statistics). The term $o(1/n)$ vanishes as $n$ grows, but we keep it as a reminder that there is a small bias correction. For our purposes, we use the inequality
\mathbb{E}[F_{\text{sel}} \mid \text{pop}] \geq \mu_n + \frac{\sigma_n^2}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right),


which holds exactly when $F_i$ are i.i.d. from a continuous distribution; for discrete or empirical distributions the inequality is approximate but can be made rigorous with a slight adjustment (see Lemma 1 in Lehre & Qin, 2022). We will assume continuous fitness or accept the approximation.

Step 2: Effect of mutation.
Let $G_{\text{parent}}$ be the selected individual and $G_{\text{offspring}} \sim K_{\text{mut}}(\cdot \mid G_{\text{parent}})$. By Assumption A1,
\mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{offspring}}) \mid G_{\text{parent}}] \geq f(G_{\text{parent}}) - L \cdot \mathbb{E}[d_{\text{edit}}(G_{\text{offspring}}, G_{\text{parent}}) \mid G_{\text{parent}}].


Taking expectation over the parent selection,
\mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{offspring}})] \geq \mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{parent}})] - L \epsilon_{\text{mut}},


where $\epsilon_{\text{mut}} = \mathbb{E}[d_{\text{edit}}]$ (which may depend on the population, but we assume a uniform bound).

Step 3: Relate $\mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{parent}})]$ to $f_k$.
$f_k = \mathbb{E}[\mu_n]$, i.e., the expectation of the population mean. From Step 1,
\mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{parent}})] = \mathbb{E}\left[ \mathbb{E}[F_{\text{sel}} \mid \text{pop}] \right] \geq \mathbb{E}[\mu_n] + \frac{\mathbb{E}[\sigma_n^2]}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right).


But $\mathbb{E}[\sigma_n^2] = \frac{n-1}{n} \mathrm{Var}(F_i)$ (unbiased sample variance). For large $n$, $\frac{n-1}{n} \approx 1$. Moreover, $\mathrm{Var}(F_i) = \mathrm{Var}(\rho(\tau))$ because $\rho$ is the reward of a single trajectory and the $F_i$ are i.i.d. draws from the distribution induced by $G_i$. Hence $\mathbb{E}[\sigma_n^2] = \mathrm{Var}(\rho) \cdot (n-1)/n$. Thus
\mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{parent}})] \geq f_k + \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\rho)}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right).

Step 4: Combine.
Substituting into the mutation bound,
f_{k+1} = \mathbb{E}[f(G_{\text{offspring}})] \geq f_k + \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\rho)}{s}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right) - L \epsilon_{\text{mut}}.


∎

