A.5 Proof of Theorem 3.4.2 (Level‑Based Convergence)

Theorem (restated).
Let $\mathcal{G}$ be partitioned into levels $L_1,\dots,L_m$ as in Definition 3.4.1, with Assumption A4 holding (for each $i < m$, starting from any $G \in L_i$, the probability that after at most $t_i$ generations the population contains an individual in a higher level is at least $\gamma_i$). Then the expected number of generations required to reach a graph with fitness at least $f^* - \epsilon$ is at most $\sum_{i=1}^{m-1} \frac{t_i}{\gamma_i}$.

Proof. We follow the standard level‑based analysis (see, e.g., Wegener, 2002; Lehre & Qin, 2022). Define $T_i$ as the first generation when the population contains an individual from $\bigcup_{j>i} L_j$. We want an upper bound on $\mathbb{E}[T_{m-1}]$ (since reaching level $m$ means optimal fitness, but we stop at $f^*-\epsilon$ which corresponds to some level $i^*$; for simplicity assume $m-1$ is the last level before the top).

For any $i$, while the population is contained in $L_i$ (i.e., no individual has yet reached a higher level), Assumption A4 guarantees that within at most $t_i$ generations, the probability of reaching a higher level is at least $\gamma_i$. This implies that the number of phases spent in level $i$ is stochastically dominated by a geometric random variable with success probability $\gamma_i$ and maximum phase length $t_i$. More precisely, let $Y_i$ be the number of generations spent in level $i$ (including the generation where the transition occurs). Then $\mathbb{E}[Y_i] \leq t_i / \gamma_i$. Summing over $i$ gives the bound. Formal justification uses the fact that we can restart the clock after each $t_i$ steps; the probability of not having progressed after $r$ blocks of $t_i$ steps is at most $(1-\gamma_i)^r$, so the expected number of blocks is $1/\gamma_i$, and each block contributes at most $t_i$ generations. ∎

Remark. The polynomial dependence on $1/\epsilon$ follows from the minimum level gap $\Delta_{\min}$: $m \leq (f^* - \min f)/\Delta_{\min} + 1$, and $\Delta_{\min}$ can be chosen as $\epsilon$ if we define levels with spacing $\epsilon$. Hence the total expected time is $O(m \cdot \max t_i / \min \gamma_i)$, which is polynomial in $1/\epsilon$ if the $t_i$ and $\gamma_i$ are constants or depend polynomially on $1/\epsilon$.

