A.6 Proof of Theorem 4.3 (Finite‑Sample PAC Bound)

Theorem (restated).
Let $\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}$ be a finite set of tool graphs. For any $\delta \in (0,1)$, with probability at least $1-\delta$,
\sup_{G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}} |\hat{f}_T(G) - f(G)| \leq \sqrt{\frac{\log(2|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}|/\delta)}{2T}}.


Consequently, for the empirical best $\hat{G}_T = \arg\max \hat{f}_T(G)$,
f(\hat{G}_T) \geq \max_{G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}} f(G) - \sqrt{\frac{2\log(2|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}|/\delta)}{T}}.

Proof. For a fixed $G$, the random variables $\rho(\tau_t \mid G)$ are i.i.d. bounded in $[0,1]$ (since $\rho$ is normalized). By Hoeffding’s inequality,
\mathbb{P}\left( |\hat{f}_T(G) - f(G)| \geq \epsilon \right) \leq 2\exp(-2T\epsilon^2).


Now take a union bound over all $G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}$:
\mathbb{P}\left( \sup_{G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}} |\hat{f}_T(G) - f(G)| \geq \epsilon \right) \leq 2|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}| \exp(-2T\epsilon^2).


Set the right‑hand side equal to $\delta$ and solve for $\epsilon$:
\epsilon = \sqrt{\frac{\log(2|\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}|/\delta)}{2T}}.


Thus with probability at least $1-\delta$, the uniform deviation is at most $\epsilon$.

For the second statement, let $G^* = \arg\max_{G \in \mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}} f(G)$. Then
f(\hat{G}_T) \geq \hat{f}_T(\hat{G}_T) - \epsilon \geq \hat{f}_T(G^*) - \epsilon \geq f(G^*) - 2\epsilon.


The factor 2 appears because $\hat{f}_T(G^*)$ is within $\epsilon$ of $f(G^*)$ with high probability. More precisely,
f(\hat{G}_T) \geq \hat{f}_T(\hat{G}_T) - \epsilon \geq \hat{f}_T(G^*) - \epsilon \geq f(G^*) - 2\epsilon.


∎

Extension to infinite $\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}$. If $\mathcal{G}_{\text{eff}}$ is infinite but has finite covering number $N(\epsilon)$ at scale $\epsilon$, one can use a chaining argument to obtain a bound of the form $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\log N(\epsilon)/T})$. The details are standard in empirical process theory (see Vapnik, 1998).

