A.7 Proof of Theorem 5.2 (Safety Closure)

Theorem (restated).
Suppose each atomic tool $v$ has failure probability $\mathbb{P}(v \text{ violates spec}) \leq \epsilon_v$. Let the monitor $\mathcal{A}_\varphi$ be synthesized as in Theorem 3.4. If mutation and crossover operators are monitor‑guided (reject any offspring that would cause the monitor to enter a rejecting state), then for any generation $k$,
\mathbb{P}(G_{k+1} \models \varphi_{\text{safe}} \mid G_k \models \varphi_{\text{safe}}) \geq 1 - \sum_{v \in \text{modified tools}} \epsilon_v.


In particular, if each modification touches at most $r$ tools, then the per‑generation safety violation probability is at most $r \cdot \max_v \epsilon_v$.

Proof.

Step 1: Monitor correctness.
By Theorem 3.4, the monitor $\mathcal{A}_\varphi$ accepts exactly those execution traces that satisfy $\varphi_{\text{safe}}$. Moreover, the monitor can be composed with the tool graph such that if any step violates $\varphi$, the monitor enters a rejecting state (or a non‑accepting state) after the violating step. Therefore, a graph $G$ satisfies $\varphi_{\text{safe}}$ for all executions if and only if the monitor never rejects during any execution.

Step 2: Monitor‑guided operators.
Define an operator as monitor‑guided if it first generates a candidate offspring $G'$ using the usual mutation/crossover rules, then simulates the monitor on $G'$ for a fixed number of steps (or until a rejecting state is reached). If the monitor ever rejects, the offspring is discarded and the operator returns the parent (or another safe individual). This ensures that any offspring that is actually deployed satisfies $\varphi_{\text{safe}}$ with probability 1 with respect to the monitor’s internal logic.

Step 3: Residual risk from atomic tool failures.
The monitor itself may fail to detect a violation if an atomic tool’s execution deviates from its specification in a way that is not captured by the monitor’s transition function. However, by assumption, each atomic tool violates its specification with probability at most $\epsilon_v$. If the mutation or crossover modifies a set $V'$ of tools, then the probability that any of them fails during the execution that the monitor checks is at most $\sum_{v \in V'} \epsilon_v$ (union bound). If such a failure occurs, the monitor might incorrectly accept a violating trace, or might reject a safe trace (false positive). We are concerned only with the probability of deploying an unsafe graph. Since we reject any offspring that causes the monitor to reject (even if due to a tool failure), the only way an unsafe graph can be deployed is if the monitor incorrectly accepts it because of a tool failure. That probability is at most $\sum_{v \in V'} \epsilon_v$. Conditioned on no tool failure, the monitor is perfect by construction.

Step 4: Conditional probability.
Given that $G_k$ is safe, the operators produce $G_{k+1}$ that is either $G_k$ (if all offspring were rejected) or a new graph that passed the monitor. In either case, the probability that $G_{k+1}$ is unsafe is at most the probability that a tool failure occurred during the monitor’s verification run of the accepted offspring. Hence
\mathbb{P}(G_{k+1} \not\models \varphi_{\text{safe}} \mid G_k \models \varphi_{\text{safe}}) \leq \sum_{v \in \text{modified}} \epsilon_v.


Taking complements gives the desired bound. ∎

