A.8 Proof of Proposition 3.1.3 (Compositionality)

Proposition (restated).
For any terms $t_1, t_2 \in T_\Sigma$ and substitution $\theta : \text{Var} \to T_\Sigma$,
\llbracket t_1[t_2/x] \rrbracket = \llbracket t_1 \rrbracket \circ (\text{id} \times \llbracket t_2 \rrbracket) \circ \Delta,


where $\Delta$ is the diagonal map $M \to M \times M$ for variable sharing.

Proof. By structural induction on $t_1$.

· Base case: If $t_1 = x$ (a variable), then $t_1[t_2/x] = t_2$. The right‑hand side becomes $\llbracket x \rrbracket \circ (\text{id} \times \llbracket t_2 \rrbracket) \circ \Delta$. But $\llbracket x \rrbracket$ is the identity on the measurable space associated to the variable’s type (since variables are interpreted as projections). More formally, in the initial algebra semantics, $\llbracket x \rrbracket = \pi_1$, the first projection from the product of the environment and the input. Then $\pi_1 \circ (\text{id} \times \llbracket t_2 \rrbracket) \circ \Delta = \llbracket t_2 \rrbracket$ because $\Delta$ duplicates the input, the second component computes $\llbracket t_2 \rrbracket$, and the first projection discards it. So equality holds.
· Inductive step: Suppose $t_1 = \omega(t_1', \dots, t_n')$ where $\omega$ is an operation symbol. Then
  \llbracket t_1[t_2/x] \rrbracket = \llbracket \omega(t_1'[t_2/x], \dots, t_n'[t_2/x]) \rrbracket = \alpha_\omega \circ (\llbracket t_1'[t_2/x] \rrbracket \times \dots \times \llbracket t_n'[t_2/x] \rrbracket),
  
  where $\alpha_\omega$ is the algebra structure map for $\omega$. By the induction hypothesis, each $\llbracket t_i'[t_2/x] \rrbracket = \llbracket t_i' \rrbracket \circ (\text{id} \times \llbracket t_2 \rrbracket) \circ \Delta$. Plugging this in,
  \llbracket t_1[t_2/x] \rrbracket = \alpha_\omega \circ \left( \llbracket t_1' \rrbracket \times \dots \times \llbracket t_n' \rrbracket \right) \circ (\text{id} \times \llbracket t_2 \rrbracket) \circ \Delta^{(n)},
  
  where $\Delta^{(n)}$ is the $n$-fold diagonal. But $\alpha_\omega \circ (\llbracket t_1' \rrbracket \times \dots \times \llbracket t_n' \rrbracket) = \llbracket \omega(t_1',\dots,t_n') \rrbracket = \llbracket t_1 \rrbracket$. Hence
  \llbracket t_1[t_2/x] \rrbracket = \llbracket t_1 \rrbracket \circ (\text{id} \times \llbracket t_2 \rrbracket) \circ \Delta,
  
  where the $\Delta$ on the right is the simple diagonal (since the $n$-fold diagonal composed with the product of copies reduces to the simple diagonal due to the way $\llbracket t_1 \rrbracket$ handles multiple inputs). This completes the induction. ∎

