A.9 Proof of Theorem 6.1 and Corollary 6.2 (Probabilistic Safety)

Theorem 6.1 (restated).
If each atomic tool $v$ satisfies $\mathbb{P}(v \text{ violates spec}) \leq \epsilon_v$, and the tool graph has depth $D$, then for a single trajectory,
\mathbb{P}(\tau \not\models \varphi_{\text{safe}}) \leq D \cdot \max_{v \in V} \epsilon_v.

Proof. A trajectory $\tau$ consists of $D$ sequential tool invocations (the depth of the graph). For the entire trajectory to violate $\varphi_{\text{safe}}$, at least one of these invocations must violate its local specification (by the semantics of LTL safety properties, which are prefix‑closed). By the union bound,
\mathbb{P}(\tau \not\models \varphi_{\text{safe}}) \leq \sum_{j=1}^D \mathbb{P}(\text{tool}_j \text{ violates spec}).


Each $\mathbb{P}(\text{tool}_j \text{ violates spec}) \leq \max_v \epsilon_v$ (since each tool in the graph is one of the atomic tools). Hence the sum is at most $D \cdot \max_v \epsilon_v$. ∎

Corollary 6.2 (restated).
With runtime monitoring (Theorem 3.4), the probability of an undetected safety violation after $T$ steps decays exponentially:
\mathbb{P}(\text{undetected violation by time } T) \leq \exp(-\lambda T)


for some $\lambda > 0$ depending on monitor sensitivity.

Proof sketch. We model the monitoring process as a martingale $M_t = \mathbb{I}[\text{no violation detected by time } t] - \mathbb{P}(\text{no violation by } t \mid \text{history})$. Under the assumption that the monitor has a bounded false‑negative rate (i.e., the probability of missing a violation is at most $\eta < 1$), the process has negative drift when a violation occurs. More formally, define $Z_t$ as the indicator that a violation has occurred but has not yet been detected. One can show that $\mathbb{E}[Z_{t+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_t] \leq (1-\theta) Z_t$ for some $\theta > 0$, where $\theta$ is the monitor’s detection probability per violation. Then $\mathbb{E}[Z_T] \leq (1-\theta)^T Z_0$, and by Markov’s inequality, $\mathbb{P}(Z_T \geq 1) \leq (1-\theta)^T$. The exponential decay follows. For a rigorous treatment, see the concept of “monitor confidence” in runtime verification literature (e.g., Bauer et al., 2011). ∎


